import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;

private void readBinaryCustomData(Position position, ByteBuf buf, String form) {
    if (buf == null) {
        return; // Handle null buffer gracefully
    }

    switch (form) {
        case "int":
            position.setInt(buf.readInt());
            break;
        case "long":
            position.setLong(buf.readLong());
            break;
        case "float":
            position.setFloat(buf.readFloat());
            break;
        case "double":
            position.setDouble(buf.readDouble());
            break;
        case "short":
            position.setShort(buf.readShort());
            break;
        case "byte":
            position.setByte(buf.readByte());
            break;
        case "boolean":
            position.setBoolean(buf.readBoolean());
            break;
        case "string":
            int stringLength = buf.readInt(); // Assuming length is prefixed
            if (stringLength > 0) {
                byte[] stringBytes = new byte[stringLength];
                buf.readBytes(stringBytes);
                position.setString(new String(stringBytes));
            } else {
                position.setString(""); // Handle empty string
            }
            break;
        default:
            // Handle unknown form or throw exception
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown data form: " + form);
    }
}
```

This solution assumes `Position` has setter methods for `int`, `long`, `float`, `double`, `short`, `byte`, `boolean`, and `String`.  It also assumes that strings are prefixed with their length as an integer.  Error handling is included for a null `ByteBuf` and unknown `form` values.  You might need to adjust the string handling or exception handling based on your specific requirements.  For instance, you might want to use a different character encoding for strings or log the error instead of throwing an exception.

