import java.net.SocketAddress;
import java.text.ParseException;

import org.apache.mina.core.session.IoSession;
import org.apache.mina.core.session.IoSessionConfig;
import org.apache.mina.core.session.IoSessionData;
import org.apache.mina.core.session.IoSessionListener;
import org.apache.mina.transport.socket.nio.NioSocketAcceptor;

class Position {
    double latitude;
    double longitude;

    public Position(double latitude, double longitude) {
        this.latitude = latitude;
        this.longitude = longitude;
    }
}


class MyChannelHandler {

    private Position decode4(
            Channel channel, SocketAddress remoteAddress, String[] values) throws ParseException {
        if (values.length != 2) {
            throw new ParseException("Invalid number of values", 0);
        }

        try {
            double latitude = Double.parseDouble(values[0]);
            double longitude = Double.parseDouble(values[1]);
            return new Position(latitude, longitude);
        } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
            throw new ParseException("Invalid number format", 0);
        }
    }
}
```

This solution assumes that the input `values` array contains two strings representing latitude and longitude, respectively.  It handles potential errors:

* **Incorrect number of values:** It checks if the array has exactly two elements. If not, it throws a `ParseException`.
* **Invalid number format:** It uses a `try-catch` block to handle potential `NumberFormatException` during the conversion of strings to doubles. If a number format error occurs, it throws a `ParseException`.

The `Position` class is a simple data structure to hold the latitude and longitude.  Remember to replace `Channel` with the appropriate channel type from your Mina library (e.g., `org.apache.mina.core.session.IoSession`).  This example also includes a placeholder `MyChannelHandler` class to show how this function might be used within a larger context.  You'll need to adapt this to your specific Mina setup.

