```java
import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;

private void readBinaryCustomData(Position position, ByteBuf buf, String form) {
    if (buf == null) {
        return; // Handle null buffer gracefully
    }

    switch (form) {
        case "int":
            position.setInt(buf.readInt());
            break;
        case "long":
            position.setLong(buf.readLong());
            break;
        case "float":
            position.setFloat(buf.readFloat());
            break;
        case "double":
            position.setDouble(buf.readDouble());
            break;
        case "short":
            position.setShort(buf.readShort());
            break;
        case "byte":
            position.setByte(buf.readByte());
            break;
        case "boolean":
            position.setBoolean(buf.readBoolean());
            break;
        case "string":
            int stringLength = buf.readInt(); // Assuming length is prefixed
            if (stringLength > 0) {
                byte[] stringBytes = new byte[stringLength];
                buf.readBytes(stringBytes);
                position.setString(new String(stringBytes));
            } else {
                position.setString(""); // Handle empty string
            }
            break;
        default:
            // Handle unknown form or throw exception
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown data form: " + form);
    }
}
```

This solution assumes that `Position` class has setter methods for `int`, `long`, `float`, `double`, `short`, `byte`, `boolean`, and `String`.  It also assumes that strings are prefixed with their length in bytes when encoded in the `ByteBuf`.  Error handling is included for a null `ByteBuf` and an unknown `form`.  You might need to adjust the string handling based on your specific string encoding and length prefixing scheme.  If you are using a different encoding for strings, you'll need to adjust the `new String(stringBytes)` part accordingly (e.g., specifying the charset).  For example: `new String(stringBytes, StandardCharsets.UTF_8)`. Remember to import `java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets` if you use this approach.

