```java
/** Binary operations on arbitrary objects.
     * @param lhs left hand side value
     * @param rhs right hand side value
     * @param kind operator type
     * @return operator applied value
     * @throws UtilEvalError evaluation error */
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public static Object arbitraryObjectsBinaryOperation(
        Object lhs, Object rhs, int kind)
        throws UtilEvalError {
        if (lhs == null || rhs == null) {
            throw new UtilEvalError("Null operand");
        }

        switch (kind) {
            case 0: // Addition
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() + ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                } else if (lhs instanceof String && rhs instanceof String) {
                    return (String) lhs + (String) rhs;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for addition");
                }
            case 1: // Subtraction
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() - ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for subtraction");
                }
            case 2: // Multiplication
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() * ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for multiplication");
                }
            case 3: // Division
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    double rhsVal = ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                    if (rhsVal == 0) {
                        throw new UtilEvalError("Division by zero");
                    }
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() / rhsVal;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for division");
                }
            default:
                throw new UtilEvalError("Unknown operator type");
        }
    }
```

This solution handles addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division for Number types and string concatenation for Strings.  It throws a `UtilEvalError` for unsupported operand types or division by zero.  Remember that you'll need a `UtilEvalError` class defined elsewhere in your project.  This is a basic implementation and could be extended to handle more operators and data types as needed.  For example, you might want to add handling for boolean operations or comparisons.

