```java
import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;
import io.netty.channel.Channel;
import io.netty.channel.socket.SocketAddress;

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

class Position {
    int x;
    int y;

    public Position(int x, int y) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
    }
}

public class BinaryDecoder {

    private List<Position> decodeBinaryE(Channel channel, SocketAddress remoteAddress, ByteBuf buf) {
        List<Position> positions = new ArrayList<>();
        // Check if there is enough data to read
        if (buf.readableBytes() < 4) {
            return positions; // Return empty list if not enough data
        }

        while (buf.readableBytes() >= 4) {
            // Read x and y coordinates.  Assuming they are 2 bytes each (short). Adjust if different.
            int x = buf.readShort();
            int y = buf.readShort();
            positions.add(new Position(x, y));
        }
        return positions;
    }


    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example usage (requires Netty)
        // ...  (Setup Netty Channel and ByteBuf) ...

        ByteBuf buf = null; // Replace with your ByteBuf initialization
        try {
            buf = Unpooled.buffer();
            buf.writeShort(10);
            buf.writeShort(20);
            buf.writeShort(30);
            buf.writeShort(40);

            BinaryDecoder decoder = new BinaryDecoder();
            List<Position> positions = decoder.decodeBinaryE(null, null, buf);
            for (Position p : positions) {
                System.out.println("x: " + p.x + ", y: " + p.y);
            }
        } finally {
            if (buf != null) {
                buf.release();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This solution assumes that each `Position` is represented by two short integers (2 bytes each) in the `ByteBuf`: the first two bytes representing the x-coordinate and the next two bytes representing the y-coordinate.  It reads data until there are fewer than 4 bytes remaining.  Remember to replace the placeholder comment in `main` with actual Netty setup if you want to run the example.  You'll need to add `import io.netty.buffer.Unpooled;` for the example to compile.  Adjust the data type (e.g., `readInt()` for integers) if your binary encoding uses different data types for x and y.  Error handling (e.g., checking for `buf.readableBytes()` before accessing data) is crucial in production code.

