import org.jsoup.nodes.Document;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Element;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Node;

import java.io.IOException;

class MyJsoupUtils {
    void outerHtmlHead(Appendable accum, int depth, Document.OutputSettings out) throws IOException {
        Document doc = new Document("http://example.com"); //Dummy document, replace with your actual document
        Element head = doc.head();

        if (head != null) {
            accum.append(head.outerHtml());
        }

    }
}
```

This solution assumes you have a `Document` object available.  The provided function takes an `Appendable` to write to, a depth (which is unused in this simple implementation, but could be used for more complex scenarios like recursive traversal), and the `OutputSettings` for the document.  It retrieves the `<head>` element and appends its outer HTML to the `Appendable`.  Remember to replace `"http://example.com"` with your actual document or provide a way to pass the document to the function.  Error handling (e.g., checking for null `head` element) is included.  If you need more sophisticated handling of the `depth` parameter or different output formatting, you'll need to adjust the code accordingly.  This example requires the jsoup library.  Make sure to include it in your project's dependencies.

