import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class StringGetter {

    private static Map<String, String> stringMap = new HashMap<>();

    public String getString(String key, String defaultValue) {
        if (key == null || key.isEmpty()) {
            return defaultValue;
        }
        return stringMap.getOrDefault(key, defaultValue);
    }


    public static void main(String[] args) {
        StringGetter getter = new StringGetter();
        stringMap.put("name", "John Doe");
        stringMap.put("city", "New York");

        System.out.println(getter.getString("name", "Unknown")); // Output: John Doe
        System.out.println(getter.getString("country", "Unknown")); // Output: Unknown
        System.out.println(getter.getString(null, "Default")); // Output: Default
        System.out.println(getter.getString("", "Default")); // Output: Default

    }
}
```
This solution uses a HashMap to store key-value pairs.  The `getOrDefault` method efficiently retrieves the value associated with the key, returning the `defaultValue` if the key is not found.  It also includes robust null and empty key handling.  The `main` method demonstrates its usage.  If you don't want to use a HashMap, you could replace the `stringMap` with a different data structure or even just return `defaultValue` directly if you don't need to store any values.

